To create a list of todos using React, we can follow these steps:

1. Set up a new React project or add a component to an existing project.
2. Create a state variable to hold the list of todos. We can use the `useState` hook for this.
3. Create an input field where the user can enter a new todo item.
4. Create a button that, when clicked, adds the new todo item to the list of todos.
5. Render the list of todos in a `ul` element using the `map` method.
6. Add a checkbox next to each todo item to allow the user to mark it as complete.
7. Add a button to remove completed todos from the list.

Here's some sample code that demonstrates how to implement these steps:
```javascript
import React, { useState } from 'react';

function TodoList() {
  const [todos, setTodos] = useState([]);

  const handleAddTodo = (event) => {
    event.preventDefault();
    const newTodo = event.target.todo.value;
    setTodos([...todos, { text: newTodo, completed: false }]);
    event.target.todo.value = '';
  };

  const handleToggleCompleted = (index) => {
    setTodos(
      todos.map((todo, i) =>
        i === index ? { ...todo, completed: !todo.completed } : todo
      )
    );
  };

  const handleRemoveCompleted = () => {
    setTodos(todos.filter((todo) => !todo.completed));
  };

  return (
    <div>
      <h1>Todo List</h1>
      <form onSubmit={handleAddTodo}>
        <input type="text" name="todo" />
        <button type="submit">Add Todo</button>
      </form>
      <ul>
        {todos.map((todo, index) => (
          <li key={index}>
            <input
              type="checkbox"
              checked={todo.completed}
              onChange={() => handleToggleCompleted(index)}
            />
            <span style={{ textDecoration: todo.completed ? 'line-through' : 'none' }}>
              {todo.text}
            </span>
          </li>
        ))}
      </ul>
      <button onClick={handleRemoveCompleted}>Remove Completed</button>
    </div>
  );
}

export default TodoList;
```
In this code, we start by setting up a state variable `todos` to hold our list of todos. We use the `useState` hook to initialize it to an empty array.

We then create a form with an input field and a button to add new todos. When the form is submitted, we take the value of the input field and add a new todo object to the `todos` array with a `text` property set to the input value and a `completed` property set to `false`.

We then use the `map` method to render each todo item in a `li` element. We also add a checkbox input next to each todo item to allow the user to mark it as complete. We use the `checked` attribute to reflect the completed status of the todo item, and the `onChange` event to update the `completed` property of the corresponding todo object in the `todos` array.

Finally, we add a button to remove completed todos from the list. We use the `filter` method to create a new array with only the todos that have a `completed` property set to `false`.

