If you want to customize the way nulls are displayed in numerical columns, you can use the `valueFormatter` property in the column definition to provide a custom formatting function. For example, you could use the following value formatter function to display the string "N/A" for null values:
```javascript
{
  headerName: 'Numeric Column',
  field: 'numericColumn',
  valueFormatter: function(params) {
    if (params.value === null || params.value === undefined) {
      return 'N/A';
    } else {
      return params.value;
    }
  }
}
```
This code checks if the value of the cell is null or undefined, and returns the string "N/A" if it is. If the value is not null or undefined, it returns the original value.

You can also use the `valueGetter` property in the column definition to provide a custom getter function that returns a value for nulls. For example, you could use the following value getter function to return the string "N/A" for null values:
```javascript
{
  headerName: 'Numeric Column',
